ce:section.ce:para:
The antibacterial efficacy of the gelatin-based films on L. monocytogenes and E. coli was determined via the colony count method (
                        Fig. 8
                        ). As expected, the neat gelatin film did not show any antibacterial activity, showing the same bacterial growth trend as the control group. However, the CD-added films showed distinct antibacterial activity depending on the concentration of CD and test bacteria. The composite films retarded the growth of E. coli while disrupting the growth of L. monocytogenes, and the activity increased as the CD concentration increased. The CD-added film showed stronger antibacterial activity against Gram-positive bacteria (L. monocytogenes) than the Gram-negative bacteria (E. coli). The growth of the Gram-positive bacteria stopped completely after 9 h of exposure with 4% CD-added film. Similar antimicrobial activity of CD was recently reported for various packaging films, including carboxymethyl cellulose and chitosan (Wang et al., 2022; You et al., 2016).
